<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-339-896  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 339 896.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DEC User  May 1989 p77(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Learn to look for trouble in your network. (part 2)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Else, Kevin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Two main areas of regular network management are performanceanalysis and troubleshooting.andP;  Performance analysis is used toeliminate bottlenecks and-or identify problems before they becomecritical.andP;  It operates on three levels: passive analysis, in whichusers report problems directly to the vendor; node testing withdiagnostic software; and testing with external analysisinstruments.andP;  Dead time, frame size, bandwidth in use, and errordistribution need particular attention.andP;  This layered approachalso applies to troubleshooting techniques.andP;  Physical link testingtraces faults through visual inspection of cables, cable faulttesting, and fault location.andP;  Link level testing determineswhether a node can send and receive packets on the cable.andP;  Testmethods include loopback and stress testing.andP;  A protocol analyzeris needed to extract packets and examine their contentsindividually.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Local Area NetworksPerformance MeasurementTestingTroubleshootingAnalysisNetwork ManagementTutorial.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>